snippet.textDisplay:
Tamles is by far one of the hardest food anyone can make. And it's not something a person can perfect for the first try so don't beat yourself down! Here are some tips for the next time you decide to make them!
1. The consistency of the masa was perfect but you don't need the butter and cocunut oil. You can just use corn oil and the chicken broth
2. The corn husks have to be hot water. It'll soften faster and you don't need to let fully dry. Just give them a shake!
3. You can try to make the popular red Chile and use it on cooked soy as a substitute for meat
4. You need to spread the masa all around the corn husk and not just in the middle
5. Don't fold the short side just fold the very long side of the tamal
6. When placing them in the pot try to make them stand up. It'll be more evenly cocked that way!
7. Enjoy it more!!! Not everyone has the guts to make them!!!
snippet.textOriginal:

2. The corn husks have to be hot water. It'll soften faster and you don't need to let fully dry. Just give them a shake!
3. You can try to make the popular red Chile and use it on cooked soy as a substitute for meat
4. You need to spread the masa all around the corn husk and not just in the middle
5. Don't fold the short side just fold the very long side of the tamal
6. When placing them in the pot try to make them stand up. It'll be more evenly cocked that way!

snippet.textDisplay: You did an awesome job!  I do a vegetarian version for a lady who's like my Mom.  I grill corn, add the street corn spices, green chillies (anaheims or pueblanos), who black beans, cilantro and rice, with a tiny bit of lime juice.  It's kinda like eloté (mexican street corn in a cup).  Then wrap the masa around the filling.  You can do a thin layer, then add the center, do a layer on top, when with the husk you can use it to close the sides so that everything is sealed inside.  You want your filling to not be too wet, or it makes it hard to seal.  You can make the 'core' and chill it, or sometimes I can get away with freezing it, but I prefer it fresh.
snippet.textOriginal: You did an awesome job!  I do a vegetarian version for a lady who's like my Mom.  I grill corn, add the street corn spices, green chillies (anaheims or pueblanos), who black beans, cilantro and rice, with a tiny bit of lime juice. You can do a thin layer, then add the center, do a layer on top, when with the husk you can use it to close the sides so that everything is sealed inside. snippet.textDisplay:
As a Mexican I can say you did your best!! & does look good!
Usually, the beans(or whatever food of choice) is stuffed not on top; the masa is usually spread evenly onto the corn husk shaped into a butterfly & stuffing in the middle & wrapping it together having the “butterfly” flaps cover the stuffing as well which is why its needed to be wrapped tightly to hold the food between the masa 😁 idk that makes sense.. it’s a lot of hard work to make tho! Lots of patience 😅

snippet.textDisplay: If you make tamales again I’d recommend making it with other ppl/family. Making tamales is always a family experience for me (my family always does it for Christmas). I’ve been vegan for 3 years now and my fam has experimented w a lot of different vegan tamales at this point. We’ve done tamales verdes/rojos w jackfruit or soy curls, we’ve made beans and rajas tamales, we’ve made some with a spinach, tomato, and garlic filling. Just keep experimenting and you’ll come up with some bomb ass vegan tamales

snippet.textDisplay: Thank you for sharing this recipe with us, Julien.  Sorry to get deep, but so much content on social media leaves no room for imperfection, and that's quite mentally exhausting for anxious creatures like me who are just out there, living our lives, trying to be kind to ourselves. snippet.textDisplay: as a white person who helps make tamales with their mexican mother in law a few times a year, I have to say you did a really good job, especially for a first try. i imagine you have an extra layer of difficulty because of the no meat/no gluten situation but the texture of your masa looks really good from what i can tell! the assembly was a little off but when it comes down to it you can make tamales however you want and the fact that you took it seriously and really tried your best really says everything. i've never had tamales with just beans but i kind of want to try it now :) keep up the good work!
